Title: The Jungle Book
Credit: Written by
Author: Rudyard Kipling
Source: Adapted from book
Draft date: 3/15/2025
Notes: Stylized period live-action; animals speak with natural mouths and stable species looks throughout. Closed jungle-and-camp world; no cartoon/photoreal mix.

===

EXT. SEEONEE HILLS - EVENING

Warm evening light over forested hills. A cave mouth opens on a rocky slope. The moon is already bright.

NARRATOR
It was seven o’clock of a very warm evening in the Seeonee hills.

INT. WOLF CAVE - EVENING

FATHER WOLF, a lean gray wolf, wakes from his day’s rest. He scratches, yawns, and spreads his paws one after another.

MOTHER WOLF, big-nosed and gray, lies with her nose across FOUR TUMBLING CUBS. Moonlight spills into the cave mouth.

FATHER WOLF
Augrh! It is time to hunt again.

He gathers himself to spring downhill.

A little shadow with a bushy tail crosses the threshold—TABAQUI the jackal, thin, mean-eyed, scrap-fed.

TABAQUI
Good luck go with you, O Chief of the Wolves. And good luck and strong white teeth go with noble children that they may never forget the hungry in this world.

FATHER WOLF
Enter, then, and look, but there is no food here.

TABAQUI
For a wolf, no, but for so mean a person as myself a dry bone is a good feast. Who are we, the Gidur-log, to pick and choose?

He scuttles to the back, finds a buck bone with meat, and cracks it merrily.

TABAQUI
All thanks for this good meal. How beautiful are the noble children! How large are their eyes! And so young too! Indeed, indeed, I might have remembered that the children of kings are men from the beginning.

Mother Wolf and Father Wolf look uncomfortable. Tabaqui savors it.

TABAQUI
Shere Khan, the Big One, has shifted his hunting grounds. He will hunt among these hills for the next moon, so he has told me.

FATHER WOLF
He has no right! By the Law of the Jungle he has no right to change his quarters without due warning. He will frighten every head of game within ten miles, and I—I have to kill for two, these days.

MOTHER WOLF
His mother did not call him Lungri for nothing. He has been lame in one foot from his birth. That is why he has only killed cattle. Now the villagers of the Waingunga are angry with him, and he has come here to make our villagers angry. They will scour the jungle for him when he is far away, and we and our children must run when the grass is set alight. Indeed, we are very grateful to Shere Khan!

TABAQUI
Shall I tell him of your gratitude?

FATHER WOLF
Out! Out and hunt with thy master. Thou hast done harm enough for one night.

TABAQUI
I go. Ye can hear Shere Khan below in the thickets. I might have saved myself the message.

He slips out.

EXT. VALLEY BELOW THE CAVE - NIGHT

From the cave ledge: a dry, angry, snarly singsong whine rises from the thickets—SHERE KHAN, a great lame tiger, hunting loud and careless.

INT. WOLF CAVE - NIGHT

FATHER WOLF
The fool! To begin a night’s work with that noise! Does he think that our buck are like his fat Waingunga bullocks?

MOTHER WOLF
H’sh. It is neither bullock nor buck he hunts to-night. It is Man.

The whine becomes a humming purr from every quarter.

FATHER WOLF
Man! Faugh! Are there not enough beetles and frogs in the tanks that he must eat Man, and on our ground too!

NARRATOR
The Law of the Jungle forbids every beast to eat Man except when he is killing to show his children how to kill. Man-killing means, sooner or later, white men on elephants, with guns—and then everybody in the jungle suffers.

The purr ends in a full-throated charge—

SHERE KHAN (O.S.)
Aaarh!

—then an untigerish howl.

MOTHER WOLF
He has missed. What is it?

EXT. SCRUB BELOW THE CAVE - NIGHT

Father Wolf pads out a few paces. Shere Khan tumbles in the scrub, muttering, burned. Tabaqui dances near him.

FATHER WOLF
The fool has had no more sense than to jump at a woodcutter’s campfire, and has burned his feet. Tabaqui is with him.

INT. WOLF CAVE - NIGHT

MOTHER WOLF
Something is coming uphill. Get ready.

EXT. CAVE THRESHOLD - NIGHT

Bushes rustle. Father Wolf drops on his haunches, ready to leap—then checks in mid-spring, shoots straight up, and lands almost where he left the ground.

FATHER WOLF
Man! A man’s cub. Look!

A naked brown BABY—soft, dimpled, just able to walk—holds a low branch. He looks into Father Wolf’s face and laughs.

INT. WOLF CAVE - NIGHT

MOTHER WOLF
Is that a man’s cub? I have never seen one. Bring it here.

Father Wolf mouths the child as gently as an egg and sets him among the cubs. Not a scratch.

MOTHER WOLF
How little! How naked, and—how bold!

The baby pushes between the cubs toward her warm hide.

MOTHER WOLF
Ahai! He is taking his meal with the others. And so this is a man’s cub. Now, was there ever a wolf that could boast of a man’s cub among her children?

FATHER WOLF
I have heard now and again of such a thing, but never in our Pack or in my time. He is altogether without hair, and I could kill him with a touch of my foot. But see, he looks up and is not afraid.

The moonlight blocks out. SHERE KHAN’s square head and shoulders fill the entrance—lame forefoot, burned pads, eyes blazing. Tabaqui squeaks behind him.

TABAQUI
My lord, my lord, it went in here!

FATHER WOLF
Shere Khan does us great honor. What does Shere Khan need?

SHERE KHAN
My quarry. A man’s cub went this way. Its parents have run off. Give it to me.

The cave mouth is too narrow for his shoulders. He is cramped as a man in a barrel.

FATHER WOLF
The Wolves are a free people. They take orders from the Head of the Pack, and not from any striped cattle-killer. The man’s cub is ours—to kill if we choose.

SHERE KHAN
Ye choose and ye do not choose! What talk is this of choosing? By the bull that I killed, am I to stand nosing into your dog’s den for my fair dues? It is I, Shere Khan, who speak!

His roar fills the cave. Mother Wolf shakes free of the cubs and springs forward—eyes like two green moons.

MOTHER WOLF
And it is I, Raksha, who answers. The man’s cub is mine, Lungri—mine to me! He shall not be killed. He shall live to run with the Pack and to hunt with the Pack; and in the end, look you, hunter of little naked cubs—frog-eater—fish-killer—he shall hunt thee! Now get hence, or by the Sambhur that I killed, back thou goest to thy mother, burned beast of the jungle, lamer than ever thou camest into the world! Go!

Shere Khan backs out, growling. Clear of the mouth, he shouts:

SHERE KHAN
Each dog barks in his own yard! We will see what the Pack will say to this fostering of man-cubs. The cub is mine, and to my teeth he will come in the end, O bush-tailed thieves!

INT. WOLF CAVE - NIGHT

Mother Wolf throws herself down panting among the cubs.

FATHER WOLF
Shere Khan speaks this much truth. The cub must be shown to the Pack. Wilt thou still keep him, Mother?

MOTHER WOLF
Keep him! He came naked, by night, alone and very hungry; yet he was not afraid! Look, he has pushed one of my babes to one side already. And that lame butcher would have killed him and would have run off to the Waingunga while the villagers here hunted through all our lairs in revenge! Keep him? Assuredly I will keep him. Lie still, little frog. O thou Mowgli—for Mowgli the Frog I will call thee—the time will come when thou wilt hunt Shere Khan as he has hunted thee.

FATHER WOLF
But what will our Pack say?

She curls around the man-cub and her own. Outside, the tiger’s rage fades down the valley. The baby sleeps against her hide.

NARRATOR
In the Seeonee hills the Law holds—and a name is given. Elsewhere, under other stars, the sea keeps laws of its own.

EXT. NOVASTOSHNAH BEACH - DAY

Cold northern light. A roaring seal rookery: fighting bulls, nurseries, surf. SEA CATCH, a scarred beachmaster bull, hauls beside MATKAH, a sleek mother seal. Between them, a newborn pup—KOTICK—whose coat is startlingly white.

MATKAH
Sea Catch, our baby’s going to be white!

SEA CATCH
Empty clam-shells and dry seaweed! There never has been such a thing in the world as a white seal.

MATKAH
I can’t help that; there’s going to be now.

She croons over the pup:

MATKAH
You mustn’t swim till you’re six weeks old, or your head will be sunk by your heels; and summer gales and Killer Whales are bad for baby seals. But splash and grow strong, and you can’t be wrong, child of the Open Sea!

Kotick paddles and scrambles by her side—does not yet understand the words.

EXT. SEAL PLAYGROUND - DAY

Tens of thousands of seal babies play like puppies on clean sand. Old seals ignore them. Matkah returns from the sea and calls. Kotick bleats. She drives a straight line to him, bowling youngsters aside.

MATKAH
So long as you don’t lie in muddy water and get mange, or rub the hard sand into a cut or scratch, and so long as you never go swimming when there is a heavy sea, nothing will hurt you here.

EXT. SURF LINE - DAY

Kotick’s first try at the sea. A wave carries him beyond his depth—his big head sinks, hind flippers fly up. The next wave throws him back. He coughs on the sand.

He learns in a beach pool: wash covering him, paddling, eye open for big waves. Days of floundering, grunting, catnaps—until he belongs to the water.

EXT. NEAR SHORE - DAY

Kotick and companions duck under rollers, ride combers, play king-of-the-castle on weedy rocks.

A thin fin—KILLER WHALE—drifts close. Kotick arrows for the beach. The fin jigs off as if it wanted nothing.

EXT. NOVASTOSHNAH BEACH - DAY

Late October. Families leave for deep sea. Fighting dies. Matkah beside white Kotick.

MATKAH
Next year you will be a holluschickie; but this year you must learn how to catch fish.

EXT. OPEN PACIFIC - DAY

Matkah and Kotick swim. She shows him how to sleep on his back, flippers tucked, nose just out. Long swell rocks him like a cradle.

MATKAH
When your skin tingles all over, you are learning the feel of the water. That means bad weather. Swim hard and get away. In a little time you’ll know where to swim to, but just now we’ll follow Sea Pig, the Porpoise, for he is very wise.

A school of PORPOISES tears through. SEA PIG, the leader, rolls a white eye.

KOTICK
How do you know where to go to?

SEA PIG
My tail tingles, youngster. That means there’s a gale behind me. Come along! When you’re south of the Sticky Water and your tail tingles, that means there’s a gale in front of you and you must head north. The water feels bad here.

EXT. UNDERSEA BANKS - DAY

Quick lessons, montage of skill:

Matkah teaches Kotick to follow cod and halibut; wrench rockling from weed holes; dart through wreck portholes a hundred fathoms down; dance on waves under lightning; nod to albatross and man-of-war hawk; jump clear like a dolphin; leave bony flying fish; take a cod’s shoulder-piece at full speed—and never stop to look at a boat.

NARRATOR
At the end of six months what Kotick did not know about deep-sea fishing was not worth the knowing. And all that time he never set flipper on dry ground.

EXT. WATER OFF JUAN FERNANDEZ - DAY

Kotick lies half asleep in warm water. He grows faint and lazy—spring in his bones. He remembers firm beaches, seaweed smell, seal roar, fighting.

He turns north. Scores of young seals join him.

SEAL MATE
Greeting, Kotick! This year we are all holluschickie, and we can dance the Fire-dance in the breakers off Lukannon and play on the new grass. But where did you get that coat?

His fur is almost pure white. He is proud—and brief.

KOTICK
Swim quickly! My bones are aching for the land.

EXT. NOVASTOSHNAH AND LUKANNON BEACHES - NIGHT

They reach the birth beaches. Old bulls fight in rolling mist.

Summer-sea fire: each seal leaves a wake like burning oil; jumps flash; waves break in phosphorescent streaks.

Kotick dances the Fire-dance with the yearlings, white coat blazing in the glow. They romp inland through new wild wheat, telling ocean stories like boys home from a wood.

NARRATOR
From jungle Law to sea Law—obedience, and the price of it, is learned again where men make camps.

EXT. MILITARY CAMP PLAIN - NIGHT

Rain and mud. A British-Indian camp under canvas. Artillery lines, pickets, the smell of animals and wet rope.

A small fox-terrier, VIXEN, bright and conceited, trots beside a TROOP-HORSE—a polished cavalry mount. BILLY, an old screw-gun mule with a swaggering limp, stands near. TWO TAILS, a great elephant, looms beyond. Yoked GUN BULLOCKS shift in the mud.

A quiet MAN (the camper) sits where the animals can be heard; Vixen belongs with him.

BILLY
I’m going back to our lines. White men who haven’t a place to sleep in are more than likely to be thieves, and I’ve a good deal of Government property on my back. Come along, young un. Good-night, Australia! See you on parade to-morrow. Good-night, old Hay-bale!—try to control your feelings, won’t you? Good-night, Two Tails! If you pass us on the ground tomorrow, don’t trumpet. It spoils our formation.

The bullocks plunge, snort, and jam their yoke on an ammunition wagon pole.

BILLY
Now you have done it. Don’t struggle. You’re hung up till daylight. What on earth’s the matter?

NEAR BULLOCK
They—eat—us! Pull!

The yoke snaps. The bullocks lumber off.

BILLY
May I be flogged with my own pad-chains! Who’d have thought of two big lumps like those losing their heads?

TROOP-HORSE
Never mind. I’m going to look at this man. Most of the white men I know have things in their pockets. I live with ’em.

The troop-horse nuzzles the Man’s breast. The Man feeds him biscuits. Vixen brags.

VIXEN
I’m coming to the parade to-morrow in my dog-cart. Where will you be?

TROOP-HORSE
On the left hand of the second squadron. I set the time for all my troop, little lady. Now I must go back to Dick. My tail’s all muddy, and he’ll have two hours’ hard work dressing me for parade.

Billy stumps off. Two Tails rumbles softly. Rain thickens.

EXT. REVIEW GROUND - DAY

Afternoon. A vast parade—some thirty thousand men. Near the VICEROY and the AMIR OF AFGHANISTAN (astrakhan hat, diamond star): the Man and Vixen in a dog-cart.

Sunshine first. Infantry in waves. Guns in line.

Cavalry at the canter—music of “Bonnie Dundee.” The second squadron of Lancers: the troop-horse, tail like spun silk, head pulled in, one ear forward and one back, setting time for his squadron, legs smooth as waltz time.

Big guns: Two Tails and two other elephants harnessed to a forty-pounder; twenty yoke of oxen behind—the seventh pair in a new yoke, stiff and tired.

Screw guns: Billy the mule, harness oiled to a wink, carries himself as if he commanded all the troops.

The Man cheers alone for Billy. Billy looks neither right nor left.

Rain again. Mist. Troops form a half-circle, then a line three-quarters of a mile from wing to wing—men, horses, guns. The line advances. The ground shakes.

The Amir’s eyes widen. He gathers reins, glances back—almost as if to cut free—then the advance stops dead. The whole line salutes. Thirty bands play together.

Regiments break for camp in the rain. An infantry band strikes up a comic march air.

NARRATOR
The animals went in two by two—the elephant and the battery mule—and they all got into the Ark for to get out of the rain.

EXT. REVIEW GROUND - DAY

An old grizzled CENTRAL ASIAN CHIEF, down with the Amir, questions a NATIVE OFFICER.

CENTRAL ASIAN CHIEF
Now, in what manner was this wonderful thing done?

NATIVE OFFICER
An order was given, and they obeyed.

CENTRAL ASIAN CHIEF
But are the beasts as wise as the men?

NATIVE OFFICER
They obey, as the men do. Mule, horse, elephant, or bullock, he obeys his driver, and the driver his sergeant, and the sergeant his lieutenant, and the lieutenant his captain, and the captain his major, and the major his colonel, and the colonel his brigadier commanding three regiments, and the brigadier the general, who obeys the Viceroy, who is the servant of the Empress. Thus it is done.

CENTRAL ASIAN CHIEF
Would it were so in Afghanistan! For there we obey only our own wills.

NATIVE OFFICER
And for that reason your Amir whom you do not obey must come here and take orders from our Viceroy.

EXT. REVIEW GROUND - DUSK

Rain eases. In the distance: elephants of the gun teams, bullocks, cavalry horses, screw-gun mules, camels—lines like a heel-rope across the plain.

NARRATOR
Children of the Camp are we, serving each in his degree—children of the yoke and goad, pack and harness, pad and load.

QUICK CUTS — NIGHT AND DAY

Mother Wolf’s green eyes in the cave; baby Mowgli asleep among cubs; Shere Khan’s lame track in mud.

White Kotick’s wake burning on the Lukannon sea; Matkah’s song on the swell.

Billy’s polished harness; the troop-horse setting time; Two Tails leaning into the gun.

NARRATOR
In jungle, in sea, in camp—the Law is the same under different stars: keep your own, protect the young, and when the order comes, stand in your place.

FADE OUT.

THE END
